{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"be56d960-ac37-4b83-88a1-19e4cac74382","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01KXMdoP3MWTxU9qQf1Wbai5","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Creating .NET 11 console app"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_0185FyUsH7X951AtuqxfJ4rT","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"dotnet --version 2>/dev/null; dotnet --list-sdks 2>/dev/null | tail -5","description":"Check available .NET SDK versions","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check available .NET SDK versions"}],"interactionId":"4c7d0ec4-74da-46cc-a067-4562c5882062","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants a .NET 11 console app that serializes a `Person` record to JSON with PascalCase property names. They want to use built-in framework features.\n\nIn .NET 9+, `System.Text.Json` added `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` as a built-in naming policy. Since the record has lowercase parameter names (`name`, `age`), C# will generate properties with those exact names. By default, `System.Text.Json` uses the property names as-is (which would be lowercase here since C# positional record parameters become properties with the same casing). To get PascalCase output, we can use `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase`.\n\n\nActually, I need to reconsider when `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` was introduced. I know .NET 8 added snake case variants, but I'm not certain about PascalCase availability. Let me think through what naming policies are actually available in the framework. The default behavior preserves the original casing, so lowercase properties stay lowercase. I'm uncertain whether `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` exists in the current .NET versions since my knowledge only extends to early 2025, but given that .NET 11 would release in late 2026, it's plausible it could be available by then. Rather than speculate further, I should test this directly with the available SDK to see what naming policies are actually supported.","outp